 induced by a single topological string.\nTopological structure.\nA vector space is an abelian group with respect to the operation of addition, and in a topological vector space the inverse operation is always continuous (since it is the same as multiplication by formula_146). Hence, every topological vector space is an abelian topological group. Every TVS is completely regular but a TVS need not be normal.\nLet formula_9 be a topological vector space. Given a subspace formula_148 the quotient space formula_149 with the usual quotient topology is a Hausdorff topological vector space if and only if formula_150 is closed. This permits the following construction: given a topological vector space formula_9 (that is probably not Hausdorff), form the quotient space formula_149 where formula_150 is the closure of formula_154 formula_149 is then a Hausdorff topological vector space that can be studied instead of formula_13\nInvariance of vector topologies.\nOne of the most used properties of vector topologies is that every vector topology is :\nfor all formula_38 the map formula_39 defined by formula_40 is a homeomorphism, but if formula_160 then it is not linear and so not a TVS-isomorphism.\nScalar multiplication by a non-zero scalar is a TVS-isomorphism. This means that if formula_161 then the linear map formula_39 defined by formula_163 is a homeomorphism. Using formula_164 produces the negation map formula_39 defined by formula_166 which is consequently a linear homeomorphism and thus a TVS-isomorphism.\nIf formula_167 and any subset formula_168 then formula_169 and moreover, if formula_170 then formula_171 is a neighborhood (resp. open neighborhood, closed neighborhood) of formula_172 in formula_9 if and only if the same is true of formula_174 at the origin.\nLocal notions.\nA subset formula_175 of a vector space formula_9 is said to be\nEvery neighborhood of the origin is an absorbing set and contains an open balanced neighborhood of formula_29 so every topological v