as a convex bounded neighborhood of the origin.\nLet formula_7 be a non-discrete locally compact topological field, for example the real or complex numbers. A Hausdorff topological vector space over formula_7 is locally compact if and only if it is finite-dimensional, that is, isomorphic to formula_223 for some natural number formula_224\nCompleteness and uniform structure.\nThe canonical uniformity on a TVS formula_37 is the unique translation-invariant uniformity that induces the topology formula_31 on formula_13\nEvery TVS is assumed to be endowed with this canonical uniformity, which makes all TVSs into uniform spaces. Therefore making sense to related notions such as completeness, uniform convergence, Cauchy nets, and uniform continuity, etc., which are always assumed to be with respect to this uniformity (unless indicated other). This implies that every Hausdorff topological vector space is Tychonoff. A subset of a TVS is compact if and only if it is complete and totally bounded (for Hausdorff TVSs, a set being totally bounded is equivalent to it being precompact). But if the TVS is not Hausdorff then there exist compact subsets that are not closed. However, the closure of a compact subset of a non-Hausdorff TVS is again compact (so compact subsets are relatively compact).\nWith respect to this uniformity, a net (or sequence) formula_228 is Cauchy if and only if for every neighborhood formula_194 of formula_230 there exists some index formula_231 such that formula_232 whenever formula_233 and formula_234\nEvery Cauchy sequence is bounded, although Cauchy nets and Cauchy filters may not be bounded. A topological vector space where every Cauchy sequence converges is called sequentially complete; in general, it may not be complete (in the sense that all Cauchy filters converge).\nThe vector space operation of addition is uniformly continuous and an open map. Scalar multiplication is Cauchy continuous but in general, it is almost never uniformly continuous. Because of this, every topological vector space can be completed and is thus a dense linear subspace of a complete topological vector space.\nExamples.\nFinest and coarsest vector topology.\nLet formula_9 be a real or complex vector space.\nTrivial topology\nThe trivial topology or indiscrete topology formula_247 is always a TVS topology on any vector space formula_9 and it is the coarsest TVS topology possible. An important consequence of this is that the intersection of any collection of TVS topologies on formula_9 always contains a TVS topology. Any vector space (including those that are infinite dimensional) endowed with the trivial topology is a compact (and thus locally compact) complete pseudometrizable seminormable locally convex topological vector space. It is Hausdorff if and only if formula_250\nFinest vector topology\nThere exists a TVS topology formula_251 on formula_8 called the &lt;templatestyles src=\"Template:Visible anchor/styles.css\" /&gt;finest vector topology on formula_8 that is finer than every other TVS-topology on formula_9 (that is, any TVS-topology on formula_9 is necessarily a subset of formula_251). Every linear map from formula_257 into another TVS is necessarily continuous. If formula_9 has an uncountable Hamel basis then formula_251 is not locally convex and not metrizable.\nCartesian products.\nA Cartesian product of a family of topological vector spaces, when endowed with the product topology, is a topological vector space. Consider for instance the set formula_9 of all functions formula_261 where formula_81 carries its usual Euclidean topology. This set formula_9 is a real vector space (where addition and scalar multiplication are defined pointwise, as usual) that can be identified with (and indeed, is often defined to be) the Cartesian product formula_264 which carries the natural product topology. With this product topology, formula_265 becomes a topological vector space whose topology is called the topology of pointwise convergence on formula_266 The reason for this name is the following: if formula_267 is a sequence (or more generally, a net) of elements in formula_9 and if formula_269 then formula_270 converges to formula_92 in formula_9 if and only if for every real number formula_273 formula_274 converges to formula_275 in formula_266 This TVS is complete, Hausdorff, and locally convex but not metrizable and consequently not normable; indeed, every neighborhood of the origin in the product topology contains lines (that is, 1-dimensional vector subspaces, which are subsets of the form formula_277 with formula_278).\nFinite-dimensional spaces.\nBy F. Riesz's theorem, a Hausdorff topological vector space is finite-dimensional if and only if it is locally compact, which happens if and only if it has a compact neighborhood of the origin.\nLet formula_7 denote formula_81 or formula_1 and endow formula_7 with its usual Hausdorff normed Euclidean topology. Let formula_9 be a vector space over formula_7 of finite dimension formula_285 and so that formula_9 is vector space isomorphic to formula_223 (explicitly, this means that there exists a linear isomorphism between the vector spaces formula_9 and formula_223). This finite-dimensional vector space formula_9 always has a unique Hausdorff vector topology, which makes it TVS-isomorphic to formula_291 where formula_223 is endowed with the usual Euclidean topology (which is the same as the product topology). This Hausdorff vector topology is also the (unique) finest vector topology on formula_13 formula_9 has a unique vector topology if and only if formula_250 If formula_296 then although formula_9 does not have a unique vector topology, it does have a unique Hausdorff vector topology.\n&lt;templatestyles src=\"Math_proof/styles.css\" /&gt;Proof outline\nThe proof of this dichotomy (i.e. that a vector topology is either trivial or isomorphic to formula_7) is straightforward so only an outline with the important observations is given. As usual, formula_7 is assumed have the (normed) Euclidean topology. Let formula_308 then formula_9 has infinitely many distinct vector topologies:\nNon-vector topologies.\nDiscrete and cofinite topologies\nIf formula_9 is a non-trivial vector space (that is, of non-zero dimension) then the discrete topology on formula_9 (which is always metrizable) is not a TVS topology because despite making addition and negation continuous (which makes it into a topological group under addition), it fails to make scalar multiplication continuous. The cofinite topology on formula_9 (where a subset is open if and only if its complement is finite) is also not a TVS topology on formula_13\nLinear maps.\nA linear operator between two topological vector spaces which is continuous at one point is continuous on the whole domain. Moreover, a linear operator formula_92 is continuous if formula_331 is bounded (as defined below) for some neighborhood formula_9 of the origin.\nA hyperplane in a topological vector space formula_9 is either dense or closed. A linear functional formula_92 on a topological vector space formula_9 has either dense or closed kernel. Moreover, formula_92 is continuous if and only if its kernel is closed.\nTypes.\nDepending on the application additional constraints are usually enforced on the topological structure of the space. In fact, several principal results in functional analysis fail to hold in general for topological vector spaces: the closed graph theorem, the open mapping theorem, and the fact that the dual space of the space separates points in the space.\nBelow are some common topological vector spaces, roughly in order of increasing \"niceness.\"\nDual space.\nEvery topological vector space has a continuous dual space\u2014the set formula_357 of all continuous linear functionals, that is, continuous linear maps from the space into the base field formula_358 A topology on the dual can be defined to be the coarsest topology such that the dual pairing each point evaluation formula_359 is continuous. This turns the dual into a locally convex topological vector space. This topology is called the weak-* topology. This may not be the only natural topology on the dual space; for instance, the dual of a normed space has a natural norm defined on it. However, it is very important in applications because of its compactness properties (see Banach\u2013Alaoglu theorem). Caution: Whenever formula_9 is a non-normable locally convex space, then the pairing map formula_361 is never continuous, no matter which vector space topology one chooses on formula_362 A topological vector space has a non-trivial continuous dual space if and only if it has a proper convex neighborhood of the origin.\nProperties.\nFor any formula_363 of a TVS formula_8 the \"convex\" (resp. \"balanced, disked, closed convex, closed balanced, closed disked\"') \"hull\" of formula_174 is the smallest subset of formula_9 that has this property and contains formula_367 The closure (respectively, interior, convex hull, balanced hull, disked hull) of a set formula_174 is sometimes denoted by formula_369 (respectively, formula_370 formula_371 formula_372 formula_373).\nThe convex hull formula_374 of a subset formula_174 is equal to the set of all convex combinations of elements in formula_376 which are finite linear combinations of the form formula_377 where formula_378 is an integer, formula_379 and formula_380 sum to formula_381 The intersection of any family of convex sets is convex and the convex hull of a subset is equal to the intersection of all convex sets that contain it.\nNeighborhoods and open sets.\nProperties of neighborhoods and open sets\nEvery TVS is connected and locally connected and any connected open subset of a TVS is arcwise connected. If formula_363 and formula_75 is an open subset of formula_9 then formula_385 is an open set in formula_9 and if formula_363 has non-empty interior then formula_388 is a neighborhood of the origin.\nThe open convex subsets of a TVS for