subset of a TVS is compact if and only if it is complete and totally bounded. Thus, in a complete topological vector space, a closed and totally bounded subset is compact. \nA subset formula_174 of a TVS formula_9 is totally bounded if and only if formula_369 is totally bounded, if and only if its image under the canonical quotient map formula_537 is totally bounded.\nEvery relatively compact set is totally bounded and the closure of a totally bounded set is totally bounded. \nThe image of a totally bounded set under a uniformly continuous map (such as a continuous linear map for instance) is totally bounded. \nIf formula_174 is a subset of a TVS formula_9 such that every sequence in formula_174 has a cluster point in formula_174 then formula_174 is totally bounded.\nIf formula_394 is a compact subset of a TVS formula_9 and formula_75 is an open subset of formula_9 containing formula_547 then there exists a neighborhood formula_464 of 0 such that formula_549\nClosure and closed set\nThe closure of any convex (respectively, any balanced, any absorbing) subset of any TVS has this same property. In particular, the closure of any convex, balanced, and absorbing subset is a barrel.\nThe closure of a vector subspace of a TVS is a vector subspace. Every finite dimensional vector subspace of a Hausdorff TVS is closed. \nThe sum of a closed vector subspace and a finite-dimensional vector subspace is closed. \nIf formula_150 is a vector subspace of formula_9 and formula_464 is a closed neighborhood of the origin in formula_9 such that formula_554 is closed in formula_9 then formula_150 is closed in formula_13 \nThe sum of a compact set and a closed set is closed. However, the sum of two closed subsets may fail to be closed (see this footnote for examples). \nIf formula_363 and formula_457 is a scalar then formula_560 where if formula_9 is Hausdorff, formula_562 then equality holds: formula_563 In particular, every non-zero scalar multiple of a closed set is closed. \nIf formu